<span id="freeTextContainer8981642120396102087">One of the all-time classics of Civil War history! Catton was a master of the language and wrote with an eloquence not often found in such texts. This is the first of his trilogy in the Centennial History, and I cannot remember how many times I&apos;ve read it since it was published in 1961. Each time, however, it&apos;s fresh and like being introduced to the 1860s all over again. He begins with the campaign of 1860 and ends this first volume with the tragicomic debacle of First Manassas/Bull Run, bringin</span>
  <span id="freeText8981642120396102087" style="display:none">One of the all-time classics of Civil War history! Catton was a master of the language and wrote with an eloquence not often found in such texts. This is the first of his trilogy in the Centennial History, and I cannot remember how many times I've read it since it was published in 1961. Each time, however, it's fresh and like being introduced to the 1860s all over again. He begins with the campaign of 1860 and ends this first volume with the tragicomic debacle of First Manassas/Bull Run, bringing to life the people and the era. </span>
