<div id="review_3323966974" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3323966974" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12369745-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1396306750p2/12369745.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3323966974?book_show_action=true">May 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/12369745-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3323966974" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14573139798384972807">It&apos;s been over half a century since this was published, and I&apos;m sure more modern works will correct errors which might be in this text, due to lack of access to materials, or just not have digested fifty years of additional scholarship, however, the work, in it&apos;s most essential parts, is solid and enduring. Having read this, and other similar works, I&apos;m still stunned by those who try to deny the essential role of the question of slavery in the origins of the Civil War. This book covers only up t</span>
  <span id="freeText14573139798384972807" style="display:none">It's been over half a century since this was published, and I'm sure more modern works will correct errors which might be in this text, due to lack of access to materials, or just not have digested fifty years of additional scholarship, however, the work, in it's most essential parts, is solid and enduring. Having read this, and other similar works, I'm still stunned by those who try to deny the essential role of the question of slavery in the origins of the Civil War. This book covers only up to Bull Run, and there is a great deal more to come. It is interesting to read during the time of Pandemic, and political strife, to see themes still with us more than 150 years later. I think that's the power of a good work of History, is to recognize that ignorance, selfishness, bigotry, are not just things of the past, and very smart people during their time, can seem like such fools in hindsight. I have done reenactments, but never of the Civil War, it never seemed heroic to me to fling massed lines of troops at cannons, and rifles, only to win by being able to endure the slaughter better than your opponent. Yet, this remains an important part of our history. I do recommend. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14573139798384972807" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


